In this article, President Donald Trump proclaims October 2020 as National Domestic Violence Awareness Month. He acknowledges that domestic violence is a widespread issue that threatens the fabric of society, particularly the American family. He highlights that more than 10 million Americans suffer from domestic violence each year, with women being twice as likely to be victims. The Trump administration has allocated significant funding to support victims of domestic violence, including funding for the Department of Justice and the Office for Victims of Crime. The administration has also provided funding for domestic violence shelters across the country. The article emphasizes the importance of protecting and supporting domestic violence survivors, especially during the coronavirus pandemic when incidents of domestic abuse have increased. President Trump calls for the recognition of the victims and survivors of domestic violence and urges the nation to continue the campaign to end domestic violence.